nd, England"},"en":{"about 1187–Deceased":"about 1187–Deceased","1187–Male":"1187–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1165–Male":"1165–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1187":"1187","about 1187":"about 1187","Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England":"Burgh by Sands, Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"del","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French (Lorraine): variant of the habitational name   Delle   2 or a masculine form of a homonymous topographic name. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Spanish or Italian preposition with fused definite article <i>del</i> ‘of the’, which forms first part of surnames such as   Del Cid   and   Del Signore  , has apparently been in some instances counted as an independent surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Delle","meanings":["German: habitational name from a place so named in North Rhine-Westphalia or a topographic name (see   Dell  ).","French (Lorraine): habitational name from Delle, a place in Territoire de Belfort. Alternatively, a topographic name, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’, for someone who lived near a prominent alder tree or trees, from <i>elle</i>, a derivative of Middle High German <i>erle</i> ‘alder’."]}]},{"name":"Sandes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Sands  .","Galician: habitational name from any of various places so named in Galicia (Spain). Compare   Sandez  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sands","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name from Middle English <i>sandes</i> ‘sands’, for someone who lived at or near a sandy place, or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Sands in Carlisle (Cumberland) or Sands Cottages in West Hoathly (Sussex). See   Sand  , of which <i>Sands</i> may sometimes be a plural form or a variant, with excrescent <i>-s</i>. Compare also   Sandes   and   Sandys  .","History: Comfort Sands, a revolutionary patriot born in 1748 at what is now Sands’ Point, Long Island, NY, was descended from James Sand(y)s (1622–95), who emigrated from Reading, Berkshire, England, to Plymouth, MA, and followed Anne Hutchinson to Westchester County, NY, and subsequently RI. In 1661 he settled on Block Island, RI."]},{"name":"Sandez","meanings":["Galician: variant of   Sandes  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":28,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":37,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":72,"year":"1259","jul